{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "Artificial intelligence gives computers ways to recognize patterns, make predictions, generate content, and assist with decisions. It powers features in phones, search engines, hospitals, factories, creative tools, and everyday services—and raises important questions about fairness, privacy, responsibility, and human judgment. This chapter introduces the ideas, uses, and people behind AI, from recommendation systems and language models to research, engineering, data work, and creative projects.",
    "title": "Artificial Intelligence in the World Around Us"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "Artificial intelligence is less like a machine that “thinks” like a person and more like a system trained to find useful patterns in data. See how an AI system can identify a face, suggest a song, translate a sentence, or estimate tomorrow’s demand—and why its results depend on the examples and goals it receives.",
      "title": "What Artificial Intelligence Actually Does"
    },
    {
      "description": "A spam filter, a medical image tool, and a self-driving car face different tasks, but many rely on the same core idea: use past examples to make a useful prediction about something new. This pattern-based view explains both AI’s surprising power and its occasional mistakes.",
      "title": "How AI Finds Patterns and Makes Predictions"
    },
    {
      "description": "Generative AI can produce paragraphs, images, music, code, and other media by modeling patterns in existing examples. See why these systems can create unfamiliar combinations, why they sometimes invent convincing errors, and how people can use them as creative collaborators rather than unquestioned authorities.",
      "title": "How Generative AI Creates Text, Images, and Code"
    },
    {
      "description": "AI already helps route deliveries, detect fraud, recommend videos, support scientific research, and assist people with disabilities. Meet the kinds of work connected to these systems—such as machine learning engineering, data analysis, user experience design, AI safety, and policy—and the practical questions their teams must answer.",
      "title": "Where Artificial Intelligence Is Used and Built"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "A Biologia investiga como a vida funciona — das moléculas dentro de uma célula às florestas, aos animais e às sociedades humanas. Ela ajuda a explicar saúde, alimentação, evolução, doenças, biodiversidade e mudanças ambientais, além de abrir caminhos para pesquisa, medicina, conservação, biotecnologia e projetos como observar uma espécie local ou investigar a qualidade da água. Questões como “por que surgem novas espécies?” e “como uma célula decide o que fazer?” tornam esse campo cheio de conexões surpreendentes.",
    "title": "Biologia: a ciência da vida em ação"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "A vida aparece em muitas escalas: genes, células, organismos, populações e ecossistemas. Essas partes não funcionam isoladamente: uma alteração em um gene pode afetar uma célula, um organismo e até a dinâmica de uma população. Essa visão ajuda a ligar fenômenos cotidianos, como crescimento, fome e cicatrização, a processos invisíveis.",
      "title": "Como a Biologia conecta genes, células e ecossistemas"
    },
    {
      "description": "A evolução explica por que os seres vivos têm características tão diferentes e por que algumas se tornam mais comuns ao longo das gerações. Adaptações não são planos perfeitos: são respostas moldadas pelas condições do ambiente e pela história de cada população. Até estruturas familiares, como asas, olhos e folhas, guardam pistas dessa história.",
      "title": "Como a evolução molda a diversidade da vida"
    },
    {
      "description": "O corpo humano é um sistema de cooperação entre células, órgãos, microrganismos e sinais químicos. A Biologia ajuda a explicar imunidade, sono, alimentação, vacinas e o surgimento de doenças sem separar saúde de ambiente e comportamento. As mesmas ideias também aparecem na agricultura, na produção de alimentos e na criação de medicamentos.",
      "title": "Como o corpo mantém a vida e enfrenta doenças"
    },
    {
      "description": "Biólogos observam padrões, formulam hipóteses e testam explicações em laboratório, no campo ou com dados. Esse trabalho aparece em áreas como genética, ecologia, microbiologia, conservação e biotecnologia, com oportunidades em universidades, hospitais, empresas, museus, escolas e órgãos ambientais. Uma pergunta simples — como quais espécies vivem em uma praça ou o que existe em uma gota de água — já pode dar origem a uma investigação biológica.",
      "title": "Como biólogos investigam a vida no laboratório e no ambiente"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "Quantum mechanics describes nature at the smallest scales, where particles can behave like waves, outcomes come in probabilities, and measurement matters. Its ideas help explain atoms and light and support technologies such as lasers, medical imaging, computer chips, and emerging quantum computers.",
    "title": "A Different Rulebook for the Very Small"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "Quantum mechanics studies matter and energy at the scale of atoms, electrons, and particles of light. At this scale, familiar pictures break down: an electron is not simply a tiny ball following a visible path. Instead, the theory predicts the possible results of measurements with remarkable accuracy.",
      "title": "What quantum mechanics describes"
    },
    {
      "description": "A quantum object can show wave-like behavior, and its possible states can combine before a measurement is made. This is not just a philosophical puzzle: interference patterns reveal these quantum possibilities, and experiments repeatedly confirm them.",
      "title": "Why particles can act like waves"
    },
    {
      "description": "The rules of quantum mechanics shape ordinary technology. Electron behavior makes modern chips possible, controlled light produces lasers, and magnetic properties of atomic nuclei help create MRI images. Even the colors of materials and the stability of atoms have quantum explanations.",
      "title": "How quantum mechanics powers everyday technology"
    },
    {
      "description": "People use quantum mechanics to model atoms, design materials, analyze light, build sensors, and investigate quantum information. Future-facing work includes quantum computers and secure communication, while hands-on projects can involve simulations, spectroscopy, lasers, or visualizing probability distributions.",
      "title": "What quantum physicists and engineers do"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "Civil procedure is the system of rules that turns a disagreement into a fair legal process. It shapes everyday disputes over contracts, injuries, housing, employment, and family matters, while giving judges, lawyers, juries, and litigants a structured way to present facts, test evidence, and reach a decision.",
    "title": "How Civil Procedure Turns Disputes into Decisions"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "See how a civil case moves from one person’s claim to a formal dispute between parties. This lesson introduces plaintiffs, defendants, remedies, and the basic purpose of procedural rules: giving each side a meaningful chance to be heard.",
      "title": "What Happens When a Civil Dispute Goes to Court"
    },
    {
      "description": "A court cannot decide every dispute. This lesson shows why jurisdiction determines which court has power over a case, while venue determines the proper place for it—and why those choices can affect the entire strategy of a lawsuit.",
      "title": "Why Jurisdiction and Venue Matter in Civil Cases"
    },
    {
      "description": "Before a trial, the parties define what they disagree about and gather information. This lesson introduces complaints, answers, requests for documents, depositions, and the way procedure turns a vague conflict into specific questions supported by evidence.",
      "title": "How Pleadings and Discovery Reveal a Civil Dispute"
    },
    {
      "description": "Most civil cases do not end with a jury verdict. This lesson looks at negotiation, mediation, motions, settlement, and trial as different ways to resolve a dispute, and shows how lawyers and clients weigh cost, risk, time, and fairness.",
      "title": "Why Civil Cases Settle Before Trial"
    },
    {
      "description": "Civil procedure brings together judges, litigators, clients, jurors, clerks, mediators, and legal aid advocates. This lesson connects their roles to real work such as preparing a motion, protecting a client’s rights, organizing evidence, or making court processes more accessible.",
      "title": "Who Shapes a Civil Case"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "El urbanismo estudia cómo se organizan las ciudades y cómo sus calles, viviendas, parques, servicios y formas de movilidad influyen en la vida diaria. Aquí aparecen preguntas fascinantes: por qué algunos barrios conectan mejor que otros, cómo una plaza puede reunir a una comunidad y cómo diseñar ciudades más accesibles, seguras y sostenibles.",
    "title": "Cómo las ciudades toman forma"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "El urbanismo reúne diseño, arquitectura, geografía, transporte, ambiente y participación ciudadana para decidir cómo crecen y funcionan los lugares donde vivimos. No se trata solo de dibujar calles: también implica equilibrar vivienda, empleo, espacios públicos, servicios y calidad de vida.",
      "title": "Qué estudia realmente el urbanismo"
    },
    {
      "description": "Una calle puede hacer mucho más que conectar dos puntos. Su ancho, sus árboles, las banquetas, el transporte y la velocidad de los vehículos cambian quién puede usarla y cómo se siente recorrerla. Estas decisiones muestran que el diseño urbano también distribuye oportunidades y riesgos.",
      "title": "Cómo una calle cambia la vida del barrio"
    },
    {
      "description": "Las ciudades pueden leerse como patrones: zonas con muchos comercios, áreas aisladas por autopistas, barrios que carecen de parques o trayectos que obligan a usar automóvil. Con mapas, datos y observación cotidiana, el urbanismo convierte esas señales en preguntas y propuestas concretas.",
      "title": "Cómo los mapas revelan problemas urbanos"
    },
    {
      "description": "El trabajo urbanístico aparece en planes de movilidad, vivienda, parques, recuperación de espacios públicos, adaptación al calor y prevención de riesgos. Quienes participan pueden colaborar como urbanistas, especialistas en transporte, analistas de datos, diseñadores de espacio público, funcionarios o integrantes de organizaciones vecinales.",
      "title": "Qué hacen los profesionales del urbanismo"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "chapter": {
    "description": "L’histoire de l’art suit la manière dont les humains créent des images, des objets et des lieux pour exprimer des croyances, raconter leur époque ou agir sur la société. Elle aide à regarder autrement un tableau, une statue, une affiche, un bâtiment ou une image numérique, en reliant formes, matériaux, techniques, commanditaires et usages.",
    "title": "Histoire de l’art : lire les images à travers le temps"
  },
  "lessons": [
    {
      "description": "Une œuvre ne raconte pas seulement la vie de son artiste : elle révèle aussi les valeurs, les conflits, les religions et les pouvoirs de son époque. On verra comment observer une image en posant des questions simples : qui l’a commandée, pour quel public, dans quel lieu et avec quel objectif ?",
      "title": "Ce que les œuvres d’art disent d’une époque"
    },
    {
      "description": "Un nouveau pigment, la peinture à l’huile, la perspective, la photographie ou les outils numériques peuvent transformer ce que les artistes imaginent et ce que le public accepte de voir. Ces changements montrent que l’histoire de l’art est aussi une histoire des matières, des techniques et des façons de regarder.",
      "title": "Quand les matériaux changent l’art"
    },
    {
      "description": "L’art ne reste pas enfermé dans les musées : il apparaît dans les places publiques, les églises, les maisons, les affiches, les monuments, les jeux vidéo et les images des réseaux sociaux. On observera comment les œuvres organisent les espaces, construisent des identités et influencent la mémoire collective.",
      "title": "Comment l’art façonne les lieux et la vie quotidienne"
    },
    {
      "description": "Les œuvres sont étudiées, conservées, restaurées, exposées et expliquées par des conservateurs, chercheurs, restaurateurs, médiateurs, archivistes, galeristes et journalistes culturels. Ces rôles s’appuient sur des pratiques concrètes : comparer des sources, documenter une provenance, monter une exposition ou rendre une collection accessible à un public.",
      "title": "Les métiers qui font vivre les œuvres d’art"
    }
  ]
}
